fstests-utils release-on-drain <backend-down-cmd> <details-dir> <out-file>

Read wq-ssh JSONL on stdin, write it through to <out-file>, and when
a worker_stopped event with reason in {drained, quarantined} appears:

  1. rsync that worker's failure artifacts (.out.bad/.full/.dmesg
     for every test it failed or timed out on) into <details-dir>;
  2. fire "<backend-down-cmd> <worker>" to destroy the VM/droplet.

Step 1 has to happen before step 2: once the droplet is gone, the
files on its disk are unreachable forever.  wq-ssh's pull-model
gives us exactly that window -- worker_stopped means the worker is
idle and ssh ControlMaster is closed, but the droplet still exists.
